00:03:16,360 --> 00:03:18,940
what those notations are all about.

70
00:03:18,940 --> 00:03:19,580
Oh,

71
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:22,160
the other notation which is truly brilliant,

72
00:03:22,340 --> 00:03:23,480
again due to Einstein,

73
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:25,220
is the summation convention.

74
00:03:26,560 --> 00:03:29,200
But the summation convention is something that's

75
00:03:29,200 --> 00:03:31,840
only to be used in the right way.

76
00:03:32,580 --> 00:03:35,680
It's to be used when you

77
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:38,780
have two indices which are the same,

78
00:03:38,980 --> 00:03:42,420
one of them upstairs and one of them downstairs.

79
00:03:42,920 --> 00:03:46,460
That's the only time you use the summation convention,

80
00:03:46,760 --> 00:03:48,920
with an upper index and a lower index,

81
00:03:48,940 --> 00:03:49,860
when they're the same,

82
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:51,600
you can set them equal to

83
00:03:51,600 --> 00:03:53,160
each other and sum over them.

84
00:03:54,300 --> 00:03:56,480
That's the Einstein summation convention.

85
00:03:56,680 --> 00:03:58,240
We'll use it all the time,

86
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:00,880
but we'll only use it in the

87
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:02,700
special form in which Einstein invented it.

88
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:06,080
If we have summations to do,

89
00:04:06,180 --> 00:04:08,740
and they're not of that special form,

90
00:04:08,920 --> 00:04:10,040
I'll write summation.

91
00:04:11,420 --> 00:04:11,940
Okay,

92
00:04:11,940 --> 00:04:12,260
so,

93
00:04:13,660 --> 00:04:15,960
let's begin with four vectors again.

94
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:18,000
Four vectors have four components,

95
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:19,899
three of which are space components,

96
00:04:20,220 --> 00:04:21,519
one of which is a time component,

97
00:04:22,419 --> 00:04:25,720
and when we're interested in the four-dimensional geometry,

98
00:04:26,020 --> 00:04:29,980
we write the components a mu,

99
00:04:30,659 --> 00:04:33,700
but we can also remember that they consist of

100
00:04:33,700 --> 00:04:35,040
a time component,

101
00:04:35,740 --> 00:04:37,500
which is usually called a naught,

102
00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:40,100
and three space components,

103
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,480
which are usually called a m.

104
00:04:43,780 --> 00:04:45,400
m goes from one to three,

105
00:04:45,400 --> 00:04:47,480
mu goes from zero to three.

106
00:04:49,220 --> 00:04:50,020
All right,

107
00:04:50,020 --> 00:04:50,180
now,

108
00:04:51,960 --> 00:04:57,280
I've written my vector with upstairs index,

109
00:04:57,620 --> 00:04:59,640
I guess it's called a contravariant index.

110
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:04,000
The contravariant index is the sort of thing

111
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,600
that you would attach to dx mu.

112
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:09,350
And the fact that you

113
00:05:09,350 --> 00:05:10,780
put it upstairs and not downstairs

114
00:05:10,780 --> 00:05:12,160
is purely arbitrary,

115
00:05:12,540 --> 00:05:15,300
but you have to put the index someplace

116
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:19,500
and Einstein chose to put the index

117
00:05:20,559 --> 00:05:23,760
associated with a differential displacement like this

118
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:25,360
in the upstairs slot.

119
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:26,500
Okay?

120
00:05:27,380 --> 00:05:30,200
And I guess I don't know who first called that

121
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:31,380
a contravariant index,

122
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:33,900
and I don't know why it's called a contravariant index,

123
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:34,620
but it is.

124
00:05:35,180 --> 00:05:38,900
And to go from a contravariant notation

125
00:05:38,900 --> 00:05:41,360
to a covariant notation,

126
00:05:41,460 --> 00:05:43,180
this is pure definition,

127
00:05:44,580 --> 00:05:49,060
a mu is the covariant counterpart of a.

128
00:05:49,400 --> 00:05:50,640
It's the same vector.

129
00:05:50,760 --> 00:05:52,940
It's just another notation for it

130
00:05:52,940 --> 00:05:54,200
or another way of describing it.

131
00:05:54,460 --> 00:05:59,440
And that is equal to eta mu nu,

132
00:06:02,159 --> 00:06:03,360
a nu.

133
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:06,860
I'll remind you what eta mu nu is.

134
00:06:07,140 --> 00:06:09,760
Eta mu nu is a collection of numbers.

135
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:11,560
It forms a matrix,

136
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:14,200
a four by four matrix,

137
00:06:14,460 --> 00:06:16,460
because mu and nu go from one to four.

138
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:20,080
And eta is just the matrix,

139
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:20,820
its components.

140
00:06:21,120 --> 00:06:21,820
Eta one one,

141
00:06:21,820 --> 00:06:22,740
eta zero one,

142
00:06:22,740 --> 00:06:23,260
whatever,

143
00:06:23,540 --> 00:06:25,860
are just the components minus one,

144
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:27,220
zero zero zero,

145
00:06:27,520 --> 00:06:29,600
zero one zero zero,

146
00:06:29,820 --> 00:06:32,460
zero zero one zero,

147
00:06:32,780 --> 00:06:34,680
zero zero zero one.

148
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,980
It's almost a unit matrix,

149
00:06:37,300 --> 00:06:39,900
and in a certain sense,

150
00:06:40,659 --> 00:06:42,540
with its relativistic geometry,

151
00:06:42,840 --> 00:06:44,960
with the funny minus sign in front of times,

152
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:45,820
time,

153
00:06:45,980 --> 00:06:47,540
it really does play the role

154
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:51,160
of a kind of identity matrix.

155
00:06:51,520 --> 00:06:52,700
But it is what it is.

156
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:54,180
Minus one in one slot,

157
00:06:54,420 --> 00:06:55,840
ones in all the other slots,

158
00:06:55,920 --> 00:06:56,960
purely diagonal.

159
00:06:59,559 --> 00:07:01,860
And what this complicated formula,

160
00:07:02,160 --> 00:07:02,360
well,

161
00:07:02,360 --> 00:07:03,140
it's kind of neat.

162
00:07:03,300 --> 00:07:03,860
It's a nice,

163
00:07:03,860 --> 00:07:04,220
neat,

164
00:07:04,220 --> 00:07:07,060
simple setup.

165
00:07:07,140 --> 00:07:09,880
But really all it says is that,

166
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:14,580
the time component of the covariant vector

167
00:07:14,580 --> 00:07:17,940
is just minus the time component

168
00:07:17,940 --> 00:07:19,460
of the contravariant vector,

169
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:21,640
that's this minus one over here,

170
00:07:21,780 --> 00:07:24,180
and all the other components are the same.

171
00:07:24,380 --> 00:07:26,560
All the other components are the same,

172
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:27,520
so we can write then,

173
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:31,800
a sub nought is minus a super nought,

174
00:07:31,980 --> 00:07:36,200
a sub m is plus a super m,

175
00:07:36,320 --> 00:07:38,260
and that's all this formula means.

176
00:07:38,260 --> 00:07:43,140
But it's been written in a kind of neat way.

177
00:07:44,420 --> 00:07:46,240
Whether you find it neat or not,

178
00:07:46,300 --> 00:07:46,860
at this point,

179
00:07:46,860 --> 00:07:47,500
is not relevant.

180
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:49,250
The point is that as

181
00:07:49,250 --> 00:07:50,800
you start doing things with it,

182
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:53,040
you will begin to find it very neat.

183
00:07:54,960 --> 00:07:59,720
So let's take it for granted

184
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:01,160
that it's a useful thing to do.

185
00:08:02,320 --> 00:08:03,000
All right,

186
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:03,280
so,

187
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:04,560
first thing,

188
00:08:04,700 --> 00:08:07,460
the formation of scalars from four vectors.

189
00:08:07,460 --> 00:08:08,920
We talked about this at least twice.

190
00:08:09,080 --> 00:08:10,420
Let me just write it down on the blackboard.

191
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:12,860
If you take two four vectors,

192
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:14,680
they could be the same four vector,

193
00:08:14,720 --> 00:08:15,920
or two different four vectors,

194
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:19,940
and you take one of them to be covariant,

195
00:08:19,940 --> 00:08:22,240
and the other to be contravariant.

196
00:08:24,020 --> 00:08:24,460
Now,

197
00:08:24,460 --> 00:08:27,180
this thing that I've written on the blackboard

198
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:30,840
automatically sums over mu.

199
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:33,299
I do not have to write sum over mu here.

200
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:34,900
By Einstein's convention,

201
00:08:34,900 --> 00:08:38,539
this means a sub one b super one,

202
00:08:38,659 --> 00:08:39,059
you know,

203
00:08:39,059 --> 00:08:39,720
sorry,

204
00:08:39,720 --> 00:08:41,460
naught one two three,

205
00:08:41,580 --> 00:08:42,840
and so forth.

206
00:08:43,039 --> 00:08:44,620
This is a scalar.

207
00:08:45,220 --> 00:08:46,360
In other words,

208
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:47,280
this is a thing

209
00:08:47,900 --> 00:08:51,320
which is a quantity which doesn't change

210
00:08:51,320 --> 00:08:52,500
from frame to frame.

211
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:56,320
Another example,

212
00:08:56,320 --> 00:08:56,980
incidentally,

213
00:08:56,980 --> 00:08:57,920
I'll just give you another example,

214
00:08:58,060 --> 00:08:59,560
the derivative sign.

215
00:08:59,860 --> 00:09:01,420
Let's just put it over here for a minute.

216
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:02,940
The derivative sign,

217
00:09:02,940 --> 00:09:04,120
d by dx mu,

218
00:09:05,620 --> 00:09:09,800
now this is a collection of four differential symbols,

219
00:09:09,960 --> 00:09:10,640
derivative symbols,

220
00:09:11,220 --> 00:09:12,940
derivative with respect to x naught,

221
00:09:13,060 --> 00:09:14,600
which means derivative with respect to time,

222
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:17,560
and derivatives with respect to the other coordinates.

223
00:09:19,740 --> 00:09:23,980
It is often just written as d sub mu.

224
00:09:24,280 --> 00:09:24,740
Okay,

225
00:09:24,740 --> 00:09:26,100
another brilliant notation.

226
00:09:26,580 --> 00:09:27,950
Get rid of the sub x

227
00:09:27,950 --> 00:09:29,320
and just write d sub mu.

228
00:09:30,480 --> 00:09:31,920
This symbol by itself,

229
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:32,440
of course,

230
00:09:32,460 --> 00:09:33,220
doesn't mean anything.

231
00:09:33,340 --> 00:09:34,620
It's got to act on something.

232
00:09:35,540 --> 00:09:37,380
But whatever it acts on,

233
00:09:37,520 --> 00:09:39,080
it adds another index.

234
00:09:39,820 --> 00:09:41,200
If it acts on a scalar,

235
00:09:41,380 --> 00:09:43,900
it creates a thing with an index mu.

236
00:09:44,920 --> 00:09:45,960
That index,

237
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:47,320
or the d by dx mu,

238
00:09:47,540 --> 00:09:48,320
or the d mu,

239
00:09:48,460 --> 00:09:50,400
is a covariant index.

240
00:09:50,980 --> 00:09:52,000
In other words,

241
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:52,620
for example,

242
00:09:52,800 --> 00:09:55,280
if this were to act on a scalar field,

243
00:09:55,940 --> 00:10:00,780
it would give you a collection of derivatives

244
00:10:00,780 --> 00:10:03,360
which form a covariant vector.

245
00:10:03,420 --> 00:10:04,320
I won't give it a name.

246
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:07,400
Its name is d mu phi.

247
00:10:08,220 --> 00:10:08,900
All right,

248
00:10:08,900 --> 00:10:09,860
so the derivative symbol,

249
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:10,220
yes,

250
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:10,400
sir?

251
00:10:10,720 --> 00:10:14,160
So it's dx sub mu,

252
00:10:14,320 --> 00:10:16,920
so the mu on the x is a covariant.

253
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:18,880
So why is the derivative a covariant?

254
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:19,640
Because it's down,

255
00:10:19,700 --> 00:10:21,500
because it's underneath the fraction bar.

256
00:10:22,660 --> 00:10:23,140
Why,

257
00:10:23,140 --> 00:10:23,700
indeed.

258
00:10:23,860 --> 00:10:24,180
All right,

259
00:10:24,180 --> 00:10:25,660
so last time I explained why.

260
00:10:26,180 --> 00:10:28,740
And I explained why if you

261
00:10:28,740 --> 00:10:31,300
take d phi by dx mu,

262
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:35,460
and you multiply it by dx mu,

263
00:10:37,180 --> 00:10:38,080
what is that?

264
00:10:38,300 --> 00:10:40,640
That's derivative of phi with respect to time,

265
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:41,420
times d time,

266
00:10:41,420 --> 00:10:42,620
and so forth and so on.

267
00:10:42,760 --> 00:10:44,540
This is just the change in phi

268
00:10:44,540 --> 00:10:46,700
as you go from one point to another

269
00:10:46,700 --> 00:10:48,840
by a differential displacement dx.

270
00:10:50,300 --> 00:10:51,700
This is nothing but,

271
00:10:51,760 --> 00:10:53,560
if we call this point two and point one,

272
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:57,480
this is just phi of two minus phi of one

273
00:11:00,020 --> 00:11:01,280
divided by a little bit of x.

274
00:11:01,280 --> 00:11:02,180
So it's a little differential separation,

275
00:11:03,120 --> 00:11:05,900
but it is just the difference of two scalars,

276
00:11:05,920 --> 00:11:07,380
and therefore itself is a scalar.

277
00:11:08,620 --> 00:11:11,080
So by a theorem that I didn't prove,

278
00:11:11,180 --> 00:11:11,960
but I told you about,

279
00:11:12,220 --> 00:11:15,760
if you have a contravariant vector,

280
00:11:15,980 --> 00:11:19,080
and you multiply it by a collection of symbols

281
00:11:19,940 --> 00:11:21,500
with a script mu,

282
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:24,520
if the result is a scalar,

283
00:11:25,070 --> 00:11:27,000
the theorem says that the thing,

284
00:11:27,140 --> 00:11:28,480
that the other piece of it here

285
00:11:29,150 --> 00:11:30,900
is a covariant vector.

286
00:11:32,080 --> 00:11:35,360
So there is a theorem which says that

287
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:38,660
whenever you hit anything with,

288
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:40,160
or in particular a scalar,

289
00:11:41,160 --> 00:11:43,720
but I'll give you some more examples in a moment,

290
00:11:43,900 --> 00:11:46,200
if you hit a scalar with d by dx mu,

291
00:11:46,340 --> 00:11:48,520
it gives you a four vector.

292
00:11:49,580 --> 00:11:51,680
Everything I'm saying incidentally

293
00:11:51,680 --> 00:11:54,340
would also be true about three vectors.

294
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,800
The only thing that you have to remember

295
00:11:56,800 --> 00:11:59,200
about three vectors is,

296
00:11:59,300 --> 00:12:01,260
if we're thinking in a purely theoretical way,

297
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:02,500
if we're thinking in three-dimensional language,

298
00:12:03,339 --> 00:12:04,780
not four-dimensional,

299
00:12:05,080 --> 00:12:07,940
everything is the same except wherever you see

300
00:12:07,940 --> 00:12:10,720
mus and nus put m's and n's,

301
00:12:12,319 --> 00:12:16,980
and the eta matrix is just the unit matrix.

302
00:12:17,320 --> 00:12:19,420
It is just the components of eta

303
00:12:19,420 --> 00:12:21,900
which sit in the spatial components,

304
00:12:22,100 --> 00:12:23,540
and for that reason,

305
00:12:23,990 --> 00:12:26,240
because eta is the unit matrix,

306
00:12:26,540 --> 00:12:29,980
there's no difference between upper and lower components,

307
00:12:31,280 --> 00:12:32,460
so you don't have to say,

308
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:34,480
if you're talking about ordinary three dimensions,

309
00:12:35,160 --> 00:12:37,600
it's unnecessary to say whether an index

310
00:12:37,600 --> 00:12:39,260
is covariant or contravariant.

311
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:41,560
They're both the same.

312
00:12:43,540 --> 00:12:44,040
Okay,

313
00:12:44,040 --> 00:12:45,720
another example of forming

314
00:12:45,720 --> 00:12:47,620
a scalar out of a vector,

315
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:48,540
well,

316
00:12:48,540 --> 00:12:50,780
one example of forming scalars out of vectors

317
00:12:50,780 --> 00:12:54,900
is just to take a mu b mu,

318
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:57,060
but another thing you can do is,

319
00:12:57,100 --> 00:12:59,760
let's suppose we have a vector quantity,

320
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:03,260
which happens to depend on position,

321
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:04,460
and also time,

322
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:05,680
x mu,

323
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:07,520
let's not write it that way,

324
00:13:08,040 --> 00:13:10,400
it's a four-vector field.

325
00:13:11,020 --> 00:13:12,960
It depends on space and time,

326
00:13:13,100 --> 00:13:15,300
and I'll just indicate that by writing x here.

327
00:13:16,920 --> 00:13:18,800
It depends on space-time,

328
00:13:19,040 --> 00:13:21,000
and therefore can be differentiated.

329
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:22,460
As it stands,

330
00:13:22,460 --> 00:13:23,780
it's a four-vector.

331
00:13:23,940 --> 00:13:25,880
It's a four-vector at each point of space,

332
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:28,160
differs from one place to another.

333
00:13:28,420 --> 00:13:30,780
You can also differentiate it

334
00:13:30,780 --> 00:13:32,080
with respect to x,

335
00:13:33,900 --> 00:13:35,380
and for example,

336
00:13:36,420 --> 00:13:39,260
you can differentiate it with respect to x

337
00:13:39,680 --> 00:13:42,060
and sum over the index mu.

338
00:13:42,480 --> 00:13:45,060
This means derivative with respect to time

339
00:13:45,060 --> 00:13:46,680
of the time component of b,

340
00:13:46,900 --> 00:13:48,880
plus derivative with respect to x

341
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:50,580
of the x component of b,

342
00:13:50,600 --> 00:13:51,720
and so forth and so on.

343
00:13:51,860 --> 00:13:53,620
This is also a scalar.

344
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:57,540
All right,

345
00:13:57,540 --> 00:13:58,560
so that's another example

346
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:00,500
of forming scalars

347
00:14:00,780 --> 00:14:05,120
from vectors by what we'll learn

348
00:14:05,120 --> 00:14:06,520
to call index contraction.

349
00:14:07,100 --> 00:14:09,620
Index contraction is the same

350
00:14:09,620 --> 00:14:11,640
as identifying an upper index

351
00:14:11,640 --> 00:14:13,440
with a lower index and summing.

352
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:15,680
That's called index contraction.

353
00:14:16,460 --> 00:14:17,720
And index contraction,

354
00:14:17,900 --> 00:14:19,440
in this kind of situation,

355
00:14:20,220 --> 00:14:21,660
takes you from a vector,

356
00:14:21,880 --> 00:14:22,680
well,

357
00:14:22,680 --> 00:14:23,860
takes you from a quantity

358
00:14:23,860 --> 00:14:25,320
which has all sorts of components

359
00:14:25,320 --> 00:14:27,920
and leads to a scalar.

360
00:14:29,360 --> 00:14:30,000
Okay,

361
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:30,540
now,

362
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:35,880
scalars and four vectors transform.

363
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:39,480
And that's their defining property.

364
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:40,600
Their defining property

365
00:14:40,600 --> 00:14:42,160
is the way they transform.

366
00:14:43,480 --> 00:14:44,180
Scalars,

367
00:14:44,180 --> 00:14:44,740
for example,

368
00:14:44,860 --> 00:14:47,240
just transform into themselves,

369
00:14:48,020 --> 00:14:50,300
transform under Lorentz transformations.

370
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:54,780
And I'm going to give a broader definition

371
00:14:54,780 --> 00:14:56,700
of what I mean by a Lorentz transformation

372
00:14:56,700 --> 00:14:58,080
than we've used up till now.

373
00:14:58,720 --> 00:14:59,880
Lorentz transformations,

374
00:14:59,880 --> 00:15:00,900
we've talked about,

375
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:02,160
were along the x-axis.

376
00:15:02,580 --> 00:15:03,680
We could have,

377
00:15:03,680 --> 00:15:04,060
of course,

378
00:15:04,060 --> 00:15:05,300
talked about a Lorentz transformation

379
00:15:05,300 --> 00:15:07,400
along the y-axis or the z-axis

380
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:08,180
and so forth.

381
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:09,300
All right?

382
00:15:09,540 --> 00:15:11,220
But there's another class

383
00:15:11,220 --> 00:15:12,560
of transformations

384
00:15:12,560 --> 00:15:14,860
which are also considered

385
00:15:14,860 --> 00:15:17,620
to be part of the collection

386
00:15:17,620 --> 00:15:18,760
of Lorentz transformations.

387
00:15:19,060 --> 00:15:21,040
And it's just rotations of space.

388
00:15:22,280 --> 00:15:23,460
Rotations of space

389
00:15:23,460 --> 00:15:26,060
is part of the collection

390
00:15:26,060 --> 00:15:28,560
of Lorentz transformations.

391
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:29,500
Now,

392
00:15:29,500 --> 00:15:30,780
once you say that,

393
00:15:30,980 --> 00:15:32,900
then you can say that

394
00:15:33,180 --> 00:15:35,780
a Lorentz transformation along the y-axis

395
00:15:35,780 --> 00:15:38,900
is simply a Lorentz,

396
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:40,680
simply a rotation

397
00:15:40,680 --> 00:15:42,760
of the Lorentz transformation

398
00:15:42,760 --> 00:15:44,260
along the x-axis.

399
00:15:44,440 --> 00:15:47,200
You can compound rotations

400
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:49,340
together with Lorentz transformations

401
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:51,340
to make Lorentz transformations

402
00:15:51,340 --> 00:15:52,520
in any direction,

403
00:15:52,720 --> 00:15:54,760
rotations about any axes,

404
00:15:54,860 --> 00:15:57,080
and just the general set

405
00:15:57,080 --> 00:15:57,920
of transformations

406
00:16:00,360 --> 00:16:02,440
which physics is invariant under.

407
00:16:02,640 --> 00:16:04,220
I'm not going to show you how to do that.

408
00:16:04,260 --> 00:16:05,780
That's not important to us right now.

409
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:08,360
The important thing is just to keep in mind

410
00:16:08,360 --> 00:16:10,540
that physics is to be invariant

411
00:16:10,540 --> 00:16:13,440
not only for Lorentz transformations

412
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:14,840
along the x-axis

413
00:16:14,840 --> 00:16:17,100
or the y-axis or the z-axis,

414
00:16:17,280 --> 00:16:19,020
but more complicated things

415
00:16:19,020 --> 00:16:20,120
where you rotate space,

416
00:16:20,440 --> 00:16:21,660
then transform,

417
00:16:22,020 --> 00:16:23,520
then maybe rotate back again,

418
00:16:24,860 --> 00:16:25,340
and,

419
00:16:25,340 --> 00:16:25,940
you know,

420
00:16:25,960 --> 00:16:27,700
it's compound rotations with...

421
00:16:27,700 --> 00:16:27,880
Yeah,

422
00:16:27,880 --> 00:16:27,900
I'm sorry.

423
00:16:27,900 --> 00:16:29,960
So when you say rotate space,

424
00:16:30,140 --> 00:16:32,980
then time is not affected at all.

425
00:16:33,040 --> 00:16:33,120
Right.

426
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:34,020
When I say rotation,

427
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:37,260
I mean time not affected at all,

428
00:16:37,260 --> 00:16:37,560
exactly.

429
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:38,920
All right?

430
00:16:39,200 --> 00:16:43,300
So what's a nice notation

431
00:16:43,900 --> 00:16:45,180
for the Lorentz transformations?

432
00:16:46,500 --> 00:16:47,100
Well,

433
00:16:47,100 --> 00:16:49,600
let's take the transformation

434
00:16:51,880 --> 00:16:54,860
of the contravariant vectors.

435
00:16:55,320 --> 00:16:56,360
For example,

436
00:16:56,360 --> 00:16:57,580
just x mu.

437
00:16:57,580 --> 00:16:58,600
How does x mu transform?

438
00:16:59,020 --> 00:16:59,860
x mu prime,

439
00:16:59,860 --> 00:17:02,420
in particular,

440
00:17:02,420 --> 00:17:03,480
x naught prime,

441
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:04,980
that's the time component,

442
00:17:05,380 --> 00:17:09,260
that's equal to x naught minus v,

443
00:17:10,940 --> 00:17:14,140
x1 divided by square root of 1 minus v squared,

444
00:17:14,220 --> 00:17:15,339
and so forth and so on,

445
00:17:15,480 --> 00:17:17,300
just the good old Lorentz transformations,

446
00:17:17,339 --> 00:17:19,480
except that I've called time x naught,

447
00:17:19,780 --> 00:17:21,660
and x I've called x1.

448
00:17:22,420 --> 00:17:23,160
All right.

449
00:17:23,180 --> 00:17:26,480
We can always write those transformations

450
00:17:26,480 --> 00:17:27,260
as...

451
00:17:27,579 --> 00:17:28,880
in the form of a matrix

452
00:17:29,580 --> 00:17:31,760
acting on the components of the vector.

453
00:17:31,960 --> 00:17:33,200
I'll show you what I mean.

454
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:38,300
We write a mu prime,

455
00:17:39,220 --> 00:17:41,800
that's the components of a certain four vector,

456
00:17:42,320 --> 00:17:43,860
in my frame of reference,

457
00:17:44,180 --> 00:17:47,480
in terms of the components in your frame of reference,

458
00:17:47,580 --> 00:17:49,680
are given by some kind of matrix.

459
00:17:50,380 --> 00:17:52,100
The matrix has entries,

460
00:17:52,260 --> 00:17:54,240
which you'll recognize in a minute.

461
00:17:55,200 --> 00:17:57,040
There's an upper index here,

462
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:01,560
and there's an upper index here.

463
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:03,440
I'm going to put a lower index down here.

464
00:18:04,060 --> 00:18:05,440
It has two indices.

465
00:18:05,580 --> 00:18:06,560
That makes it a matrix.

466
00:18:07,340 --> 00:18:10,140
It has a value for every mu and every nu.

467
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:11,600
It's a 4 by 4 matrix,

468
00:18:12,080 --> 00:18:16,080
and now it multiplies a nu.

469
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:20,360
Is this a properly formed equation over here?

470
00:18:20,780 --> 00:18:21,260
Yeah.

471
00:18:21,340 --> 00:18:23,960
The left-hand side has an index mu,

472
00:18:24,120 --> 00:18:26,060
which can be any one of 1 to 4.

473
00:18:26,480 --> 00:18:27,560
The right-hand side has an index mu,

474
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:32,200
but the index nu is summed over.

475
00:18:32,360 --> 00:18:34,020
When the index nu is summed over,

476
00:18:34,160 --> 00:18:38,280
it's not an explicit variable in the equation.

477
00:18:38,900 --> 00:18:39,640
And so,

478
00:18:39,640 --> 00:18:39,860
yes,

479
00:18:39,860 --> 00:18:41,200
this is a properly formed equation,

480
00:18:42,180 --> 00:18:43,160
summation convention.

481
00:18:45,480 --> 00:18:46,160
All right,

482
00:18:46,160 --> 00:18:47,920
so let me give you an example

483
00:18:48,560 --> 00:18:50,500
of the matrix L,

484
00:18:51,160 --> 00:18:53,260
just for the simplest Lorentz transformation

485
00:18:53,260 --> 00:18:54,280
that we've written down.

486
00:18:54,360 --> 00:18:55,240
I'll give you a couple of them.

487
00:18:56,180 --> 00:18:57,540
For the matrix L,

488
00:18:58,060 --> 00:18:59,380
the Lorentz transformation,

489
00:18:59,500 --> 00:19:01,540
let's say along the x-axis.

490
00:19:02,440 --> 00:19:04,400
Let's just write down what we would put in here.

491
00:19:04,440 --> 00:19:05,160
We would put in here,

492
00:19:05,620 --> 00:19:08,520
this is the time x,

493
00:19:08,520 --> 00:19:09,040
y,

494
00:19:09,040 --> 00:19:09,440
z.

495
00:19:10,640 --> 00:19:12,680
Time in the first column in the first row,

496
00:19:12,680 --> 00:19:13,500
x,

497
00:19:13,500 --> 00:19:13,840
y,

498
00:19:13,840 --> 00:19:14,080
z.

499
00:19:14,460 --> 00:19:15,820
So there's a 1 over square

500
00:19:15,820 --> 00:19:17,180
root of 1 minus v squared here.

501
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:20,500
There's a minus,

502
00:19:21,020 --> 00:19:22,270
I think I better make

503
00:19:22,270 --> 00:19:23,520
this matrix a little bit bigger.

504
00:19:27,580 --> 00:19:28,080
Okay,

505
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:29,120
let's make it bigger.

506
00:19:31,160 --> 00:19:32,520
In the upper corner here,

507
00:19:32,680 --> 00:19:36,660
we have 1 over root 1 minus v squared,

508
00:19:37,330 --> 00:19:39,285
and then we have minus v

509
00:19:39,285 --> 00:19:41,240
over root 1 minus v squared.

510
00:19:41,320 --> 00:19:42,220
How about the next one?

511
00:19:42,980 --> 00:19:43,980
Anybody want to guess?

512
00:19:46,100 --> 00:19:46,600
Zero.

513
00:19:49,180 --> 00:19:49,680
Zero.

514
00:19:50,200 --> 00:19:51,320
What about down here?

515
00:19:57,560 --> 00:20:00,620
Minus v over square root of 1 minus v squared.

516
00:20:03,240 --> 00:20:05,320
And in the next place here,

517
00:20:05,520 --> 00:20:08,540
1 over square root of 1 minus v squared.

518
00:20:10,680 --> 00:20:11,260
Zero,

519
00:20:11,260 --> 00:20:11,500
zero.

520
00:20:13,580 --> 00:20:14,160
Zero,

521
00:20:14,160 --> 00:20:14,620
zero.

522
00:20:15,290 --> 00:20:15,580
Zero,

523
00:20:15,580 --> 00:20:15,940
zero.

524
00:20:16,140 --> 00:20:17,320
But what down here?

525
00:20:18,600 --> 00:20:19,840
1 and 1.

526
00:20:25,100 --> 00:20:28,680
This is a standard Lorentz transformation along the x-axis.

527
00:20:29,220 --> 00:20:31,040
And if we write a column vector,

528
00:20:32,320 --> 00:20:32,760
T,

529
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:33,200
x,

530
00:20:33,200 --> 00:20:33,880
y,

531
00:20:33,880 --> 00:20:34,560
z,

532
00:20:39,040 --> 00:20:40,940
which I could also write x-naught,

533
00:20:40,940 --> 00:20:41,380
x-1,

534
00:20:41,380 --> 00:20:41,740
x-2,

535
00:20:41,740 --> 00:20:42,120
x-3,

536
00:20:42,180 --> 00:20:43,220
but let's write it this way.

537
00:20:43,540 --> 00:20:43,980
T,

538
00:20:43,980 --> 00:20:45,120
x,

539
00:20:45,120 --> 00:20:45,980
y,

540
00:20:45,980 --> 00:20:47,160
z.

541
00:20:48,260 --> 00:20:50,800
And we write that this is equal to T prime,

542
00:20:51,100 --> 00:20:52,020
x prime,

543
00:20:52,020 --> 00:20:53,120
y prime,

544
00:20:53,120 --> 00:20:53,820
z prime,

545
00:20:54,540 --> 00:20:56,080
let's just see that that's correct.

546
00:20:56,400 --> 00:20:57,880
This is a column vector here.

547
00:21:00,520 --> 00:21:01,800
This is a column vector.

548
00:21:03,560 --> 00:21:04,560
What does it say?

549
00:21:04,600 --> 00:21:07,940
It says T prime is equal to 1 over blah,

550
00:21:07,940 --> 00:21:08,100
blah,

551
00:21:08,100 --> 00:21:08,240
blah,

552
00:21:08,260 --> 00:21:11,220
times T minus v over blah,

553
00:21:11,220 --> 00:21:11,440
blah,

554
00:21:11,440 --> 00:21:11,580
blah,

555
00:21:11,580 --> 00:21:12,640
times x.

556
00:21:13,140 --> 00:21:13,660
Well,

557
00:21:13,660 --> 00:21:15,620
that's the right transformation law for T prime.

558
00:21:16,080 --> 00:21:21,420
X prime is minus v over square root times T

559
00:21:22,100 --> 00:21:22,620
plus,

560
00:21:23,840 --> 00:21:25,600
1 over square root times x.

561
00:21:25,880 --> 00:21:29,080
That's the standard Lorentz transformation on x.

562
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:31,000
And then y and z,

563
00:21:31,580 --> 00:21:34,180
they do not mix with T and x.

564
00:21:34,620 --> 00:21:35,620
y and z,

565
00:21:35,620 --> 00:21:37,580
the unit matrix down here tells you that

566
00:21:37,580 --> 00:21:38,940
y prime is equal to y,

567
00:21:39,140 --> 00:21:40,700
and z prime is equal to z.

568
00:21:40,980 --> 00:21:41,500
Good.

569
00:21:42,660 --> 00:21:46,620
So this is an example of a Lorentz matrix.

570
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:49,820
A Lorentz matrix along the x-axis.

571
00:21:50,040 --> 00:21:53,680
If we wanted to transform along the y-axis,

572
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:57,100
we would just shuffle these around a little bit.

573
00:21:57,160 --> 00:21:58,500
I'll leave it to you to

574
00:21:58,500 --> 00:21:59,840
figure out what our Lorentz transformation

575
00:21:59,840 --> 00:22:02,800
along the y-axis looks like in this matrix notation.

576
00:22:03,780 --> 00:22:08,880
But let's consider instead a different operation,

577
00:22:09,160 --> 00:22:12,100
a rotation in the y-z plane in

578
00:22:12,100 --> 00:22:15,040
which T and x are completely left alone.

579
00:22:15,740 --> 00:22:17,680
